	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Having a custom controller made with cat5, if you think NES controllers feel the same as solid core cat5, you're delusional. Just flex it some with a cloth in one hand, going down it, that's as good as you'll get.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>mikejmoffitt</b> [ Sat Aug 31, 2013 9:43 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've had Famicom controllers be stiff like this, while others are nicer, flexible rubber. His description of solid-core cat5 is not far off. They certainly aren't designed like that nor common, but I have found controllers that have become like that.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>infiniteneslives</b> [ Sun Sep 01, 2013 10:41 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />your cords are weathered and old.  They probably got left somewhere that they saw a lot of sunlight or something.  If you're good with a soldering iron you could get a replacement cord and swap it out.  Dog-bone top loader controllers have  a special connector inside similar to SNES controllers.  Original rectangle NES controllers don't have that connector, that's why you'd have to use a soldering iron. The other option is just replace the controller with one that doesn't have such a weathered cord.  They weren't stiff like that originally.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Sun Sep 01, 2013 10:44 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The NES and SNES controllers have some of the most flexible game controller cables I've ever used. I've cut them and tried to strip them in the past and they're awful for it, since the &quot;wire&quot; is a thin copper ribbon in a spiral shape (like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rna" class="postlink">RNA</a>) around some string-like fibers. I think this configuration makes the wires almost stretch-proof, since stretching just tightens the spiral and doesn't stress the copper at all, so it never breaks.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>infiniteneslives</b> [ Sun Sep 01, 2013 10:55 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I've cut them and tried to strip them in the past and they're awful for it.</div><br /><br />Very true.  It's possible but tricky at best.  Any connection you make with them afterwards needs to have a good stress relief on it.  Because it's easy to break the fragile strands.  It's like coiled up tiny strands of aluminum foil, just slightly better since it's copper.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sun Sep 01, 2013 12:05 pm ]</td>
