	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">since the &quot;wire&quot; is a thin copper ribbon in a spiral shape (like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rna" class="postlink">RNA</a>) around some string-like fibers.</div><br />I looked it up, and you're probably right about why Nintendo chose to use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wire#Solid_versus_stranded" class="postlink">stranded wire</a>. Wikipedia says it's &quot;used when higher resistance to metal fatigue is required.&quot;

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>infiniteneslives</b> [ Sun Sep 01, 2013 12:32 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can i make my Top Loader controller's cable a bit softer</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">since the &quot;wire&quot; is a thin copper ribbon in a spiral shape (like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rna" class="postlink">RNA</a>) around some string-like fibers.</div><br />I looked it up, and you're probably right about why Nintendo chose to use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wire#Solid_versus_stranded" class="postlink">stranded wire</a>. Wikipedia says it's &quot;used when higher resistance to metal fatigue is required.&quot;</div><br /><br />Yeah but typical stranded wire is drastically different than Nintendo's 'helical coiled foil strands'.  Typical stranded wire is durable even when striped of it's insulation.  Nintendo's design allows the cost to be reduced by using less copper, but still provide decent durability and flexibility when fully insulated.  NES cords also contain a cotton string inside to provide strength and resistance from being pulled on so all the stress isn't put on the wires.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


